rom Intuition to Logic -- tPART THREE THE NATURE AND LIMITS OF NATURALIZATION -- tPhilosophical Strategies of Naturalization -- tCHAPTER FIFTEEN Naturalizing Phenomenology? Dretske on Qualia -- tCHAPTER SIXTEEN The Immediately Given as Ground and Background -- tCHAPTER SEVENTEEN When Transcendental Genesis Encounters the Naturalization Project -- tSkeptical Attitudes -- tCHAPTER EIGHTEEN Sense and Continuum in Husserl -- tCHAPTER NINETEEN Cognitive Psychology and the Transcendental Theory of Knowledge -- tCHAPTER TWENTY The Movement of the Living as the Originary Foundation of Perceptual Intentionality -- tHistorical Perspectives -- tCHAPTER TWENTY-ONE Philosophy and Cognition: Historical Roots -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX OF PERSONS -- tINDEX OF TOPICS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis ambitious work aims to shed new light on the relations between Husserlian phenomenology and the present-day efforts toward a scientific theory of cognition—with its complex structure of disciplines, levels of explanation, and conflicting hypotheses. The book’s primary goal is not to present a new exegesis of Husserl’s writings, although it does not dismiss the importance of such interpretive and critical work. Rather, the contributors assess the extent to which the kind of phenomenological investigation Husserl initiated favors the construction of a scientific theory of cognition, particularly in contributing to specific contemporary theories either by complementing or by questioning them. What clearly emerges is that Husserlian phenomenology cannot become instrumental in developing cognitive science without undergoing a substantial transformation. Therefore, the central concern of this book is not only the progress of contemporary theories of cognition but also the reorientation of Husserlian phenomenology. Because a single volume could never encompass the numerous facets of this dual aim, the contributors focus on the issue of naturalization. This perspective is far-reaching enough to allow for the coverage of a great variety of topics, ranging from general structures of intentionality, to the nature of the founding epistemological and ontological principles of cognitive science, to analyses of temporality and perception and the mathematical modeling of their phenomenological description. This book, then, is a collective reflection on the possibility of utilizing a naturalized Husserlian phenomenology to contribute to a scientific theory of cognition that fills the explanatory gap between the phenomenological mind and brain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aBarbaras, Renaud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBotero, Juan-José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasati, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDepraz, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupuy, Jean-Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFollesdal, Dagfinn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongo, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcintyre, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoe, Alva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPacherie, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPachoud, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPachoud, Bernard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPessoa, Luiz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPet